                <div class="span8">
                  <h2>
                    <a
                      href="/untyping/2005/07/14/pricing-and-differentiation/"
                      rel="bookmark"
                      title="Permanent Link to Pricing and Differentiation"
                      >Pricing and Differentiation</a
                    >
                  </h2>

                  <div class="entry">
                    <p>
                      Tom Evslin writes a <a
                        href="http://blog.tomevslin.com/2005/06/pricing_consult.html"
                        >great post</a
                      >
                      on the importance of pricing, and in particular not under-pricing
                      oneself:
                    </p>
                    <blockquote>
                      <p>
                        I won an argument with an IBM SE on the very<br />
                        good grounds that I was more expensive than him; my<br
                        />
                        recommendations for system changes were implemented<br
                        />
                        (grumpily) and some of them worked. We got a much bigger<br
                        />
                        consulting job after that which I’ll probably blog about<br
                        />
                        some day because it’s an interesting story.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        The moral for today is one that every maker of luxury<br
                        />
                        goods already knows: price can create a perception of value.<br
                        />
                        As a consultant, you need high perceived value or no one<br
                        />
                        will give you the time of day let alone their watch. And,<br
                        />
                        if you don’t have the respect you need to get information
                        or<br />
                        to have your recommendations tried, you can’t succeed.
                      </p>
                    </blockquote>
                    <p>
                      It’s a good point. Particularly when starting out, and<br
                      />
                      overheads are low, it is very tempting to sell on the basis<br
                      />
                      of price. We’ve done so in the past and the results have<br
                      />
                      been bad: the client hasn’t respected our time and<br />
                      has given us the run-around.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      If you’re in this situation you’re probably thinking<br />
                      “if I raise my prices all lose all my<br />
                      clients!” Particularly in fields such as web<br />
                      development, where there is so much competition, this is a<br
                      />
                      valid concern. So what to do about it? Well let’s think<br
                      />
                      about why high prices work. As Tom says, it is because of<br
                      />
                      the perception of value they create. Which is to say it<br
                      />
                      seems to the client that your high-priced service is better<br
                      />
                      than the competition’s lower-priced one. There are many<br
                      />
                      other ways to give the client this impression. For example,<br
                      />
                      you can write articles that show the breadth and depth of<br
                      />
                      your learning. As you’ve probably guessed, Untyping is just<br
                      />
                      such as effort. Management gurus call this differentiation,<br
                      />
                      and the more competitive the market the more essential it<br
                      />
                      is.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      So there it is. You can’t charge high prices if the<br />
                      client thinks they’ll get the same service from your<br />
                      lower-priced competitors. You must differentiate yourself.<br
                      />
                      Paradoxically price indeed is one way to do this, but in<br
                      />
                      many cases not the best way, and can be deterimental if you<br
                      />
                      haven’t already established a reputation in other ways.
                    </p>
